<doc id="331569" wikidata="Q364138" url="?curid=331569" title="Happened-before">
<text>In computer science, the happened-before relation (denoted: formula_1) is a relation between the result of two events, such that if one event should happen before another event, the result must reflect that, even if those events are in reality executed out of order (usually to optimize program flow). This involves ordering events based on the potential causal relationship of pairs of events in a concurrent system, especially asynchronous distributed systems. It was formulated by Leslie Lamport.

The happened-before relation is formally defined as the least strict partial order on events such that:
* If events formula_2 and formula_3 occur on the same process, formula_4 if the occurrence of event formula_2 preceded the occurrence of event formula_3.
* If event formula_2 is the sending of a message and event formula_3 is the reception of the message sent in event formula_2, formula_4.

If two events happen in different isolated processes (that do not exchange messages directly or indirectly via third-party processes), then the two processes are said to be concurrent, that is neither formula_11 nor formula_12 is true. 

If there are other causal relationships between events in a given system, such as between the creation of a process and its first event, these relationships are also added to the definition.
For example, in some programming languages such as Java, C, C++ or Rust, a happens-before edge exists if memory written to by statement A is visible to statement B, that is, if statement A completes its write before statement B starts its read.

Like all strict partial orders, the happened-before relation is &quot;transitive&quot;, &quot;irreflexive&quot; (and vacuously, &quot;asymmetric&quot;), i.e.:
* formula_13, if formula_4 and formula_15, then formula_16 (transitivity). This means that for any three events formula_17, if formula_18 happened before formula_19, and formula_19 happened before formula_21, then formula_18 must have happened before formula_21.
* formula_24 (irreflexivity). This means that no event can happen before itself.
* formula_25 if formula_11 then formula_27 (asymmetry). This means that for any two events formula_28, if formula_18 happened before formula_19 then formula_19 cannot have happened before formula_18.

Let us observe that the asymmetry property directly follows from the previous properties: by contradiction, let us suppose that formula_25 we have formula_4 and formula_12. Then by transitivity we have formula_36 which contradicts irreflexivity.

The processes that make up a distributed system have no knowledge of the happened-before relation unless they use a logical clock, like a Lamport clock or a vector clock. This allows one to design algorithms for mutual exclusion, and tasks like debugging or optimising distributed systems.

==See also==
* Race condition
* Java memory model
* Lamport timestamps
* Logical clock

