# Choose an arbitrary formula_12 and formula_13. Then, applying axiom [K1], formula_14, implying [K2].
# Choose formula_15 and an arbitrary formula_16. Then, applying axiom [K1], formula_17, which is [K3].
# Choose arbitrary formula_18. Applying axioms [K1]–[K3], one derives [K4].

Alternatively, had proposed a weaker axiom that only entails [K2]–[K4]:

Requirement [K1] is independent of [M] : indeed, if formula_19, the operator formula_20 defined by the constant assignment formula_21 satisfies [M] but does not preserve the empty set, since formula_22. Notice that, by definition, any operator satisfying [M] is a Moore closure operator.

A more symmetric alternative to [M] was also proven by M. O. Botelho and M. H. Teixeira to imply axioms [K2]–[K4]:
== Analogous structures ==
=== Interior, exterior and boundary operators ===
A dual notion to Kuratowski closure operators is that of Kuratowski interior operator, which is a map formula_23 satisfying the following similar requirements:

For these operators, one can reach conclusions that are completely analogous to what was inferred for Kuratowski closures. For example, all Kuratowski interior operators are &quot;isotonic&quot;, i.e. they satisfy [K4&#x27;], and because of intensivity [I2], it is possible to weaken the equality in [I3] to a simple inclusion.

The duality between Kuratowski closures and interiors is provided by the natural complement operator on formula_2, the map formula_25 sending formula_26. This map is an orthocomplementation on the power set lattice, meaning it satisfies De Morgan&#x27;s laws: if formula_27 is an arbitrary set of indices and formula_28,
formula_29

By employing these laws, together with the defining properties of formula_30, one can show that any Kuratowski interior induces a Kuratowski closure (and vice versa), via the defining relation formula_31 (and formula_32). Every result obtained concerning formula_4 may be converted into a result concerning formula_34 by employing these relations in conjunction with the properties of the orthocomplementation formula_30.

 further provides analogous axioms for Kuratowski exterior operators and Kuratowski boundary operators, which also induce Kuratowski closures via the relations formula_36 and formula_37.

=== Abstract operators ===

Notice that axioms [K1]–[K4] may be adapted to define an &quot;abstract&quot; unary operation formula_38 on a general bounded lattice formula_39, by formally substituting set-theoretic inclusion with the partial order associated to the lattice, set-theoretic union with the join operation, and set-theoretic intersections with the meet operation; similarly for axioms [I1]–[I4]. If the lattice is orthocomplemented, these two abstract operations induce one another in the usual way. Abstract closure or interior operators can be used to define a generalized topology on the lattice.

Since neither unions nor the empty set appear in the requirement for a Moore closure operator, the definition may be adapted to define an abstract unary operator formula_40 on an arbitrary poset formula_41.

== Connection to other axiomatizations of topology ==

=== Induction of topology from closure ===
A closure operator naturally induces a topology as follows. Let formula_1 be an arbitrary set. We shall say that a subset formula_43 is closed with respect to a Kuratowski closure operator formula_44 if and only if it is a &quot;fixed point&quot; of said operator, or in other words it is &quot;stable under&quot; formula_4, i.e. formula_46. The claim is that the family of all subsets of the total space that are complements of closed sets satisfies the three usual requirements for a topology, or equivalently, the family formula_47 of all closed sets satisfies the following:
Notice that, by idempotency [K3], one may succinctly write formula_48.
[T1] By extensivity [K2], formula_49 and since closure maps the power set of formula_1 into itself (that is, the image of any subset is a subset of formula_1), formula_52 we have formula_53. Thus formula_54. The preservation of the empty set [K1] readily implies formula_55.

[T2] Next, let formula_56 be an arbitrary set of indices and let formula_57 be closed for every formula_58. By extensivity [K2], formula_59. Also, by isotonicity [K4&#x27;], if formula_60for all indices formula_61, then formula_62 for all formula_61, which implies formula_64. Therefore, formula_65, meaning formula_66.

[T3] Finally, let formula_56 be a finite set of indices and let formula_57 be closed for every formula_69. From the preservation of binary unions [K4], and using induction on the number of subsets of which we take the union, we have formula_70. Thus, formula_71.
=== Induction of closure from topology ===

